    <section class="datasci_info datasci_datacol" id="datasci_datacol">
        <div class="ds_content" style="margin-top: 0px">
            <h2>Data Collection</h2><br/>
            <p style="text-indent:2rem;">
                Our proposal concentrated on the plastic polymers most prevalent in marine environments. These include high-density polyethylene used for bottles, low-density polyethylene for bags, polypropylene for containers, and polystyrene for styrofoam. The four datasets encompass items from these four plastic types under varying conditions.
                <br /><br />The Marine Debris Archive (MARIDA) dataset was utilized as the primary resource to train the model and its convolutional neural network (CNN) components. MARIDA provides images of marine debris commonly found in coastal and aquatic environments, including plastics, and other waste types from the satellite Sentinel-2. Additionally, we will be utilizing garbage classification dataset from Kaggle dataset which offers a well-organized collection of labeled images representing various waste types of plastics.
            </p>
            <div class="ds_img_right">
                <img src="~/images/DataScience/ds-1.png" alt="Placeholder Image">
            </div>
            <h2>Data warehousing and cleansing</h2>
            <p class="span_two" style="text-indent:2rem;">
                Amazon S3’s integration capabilities with machine learning workflows make it ideal for handling large datasets critical to this project. S3 allows integration with the image annotation tool Computer Vision Annotation Tool (CVAT) and it will be used as the primary storage for the Kaggle and MARIDA dataset.
                For the heatmap, Amazon S3 will also be used to store images collected from drones, ensuring scalable storage for processing by the AI model. These images will be organized into structured sections, categorized by location and date, allowing easy retrieval for the AI model. Once processed, the model will use the data to generate heatmaps, highlighting areas of high plastic pollution.
            </p>

            <div class="ds_img_left">
                <img src="~/images/DataScience/ds-3.png" alt="Placeholder Image">
            </div>
            <div>
                <h2>Data Visualization</h2>
                <p style="text-indent:2rem;">
                    Pie charts and bar graphs will be used to visualize the distribution of different classes of litter identified by the AI model (e.g., water bottles, styrofoam, bags, and other plastic types). The pie graph will be utilized to show the percentage distribution of litter classes while the bar graph will show the present the relative count of each litter class. These graphs will provide a clear and quantitative breakdown of the proportions and amounts of various litter types.
                    <br /><br />
                    Heatmaps will be used to represent the spatial concentration of plastic waste across surveyed aquatic environments. These visualizations will overlay detected plastic pollution onto a map, highlighting regions with high or low concentrations of waste. A heatmap on the live website might show red zones for areas with heavy plastic pollution and green zones for cleaner areas. For instance, a mangrove forest might appear as a red hotspot, while an open water area might show minimal plastic concentration.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
